        "content": "<p>I'm updating some code from about a year ago and having trouble working with products/exponents. I think it boils down to my confusion over this:</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">CategoryTheory</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Category</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Basic</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">import</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">Mathlib</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">CategoryTheory</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Closed</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Cartesian</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">open</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">CategoryTheory</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">CartesianClosed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">MonoidalCategory</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">example</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Category</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">ChosenFiniteProducts</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">CartesianClosed</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">A</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">B</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">T</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">A</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⨯</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">A</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟹</span><span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">B</span><span class=\"o\">))</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">⟶</span><span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">B</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">by</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"k\">have</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">exp</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">ev</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">A</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">app</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">B</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"n\">simp</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"k\">at</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">h</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"c1\">-- left with `h : A ⊗ (A ⟹ B) ⟶ B`</span>\n<span class=\"w\">  </span><span class=\"gr\">sorry</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>Previously simp wouldn't have been needed at all, this would immediately be defeq.</p>",
        "id": 519204124,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Henson",
        "timestamp": 1747683057
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>What commit are you updating against? Recently (<a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/24390\">#24390</a>), <code>ChosenFiniteProduct</code> has been deprecated and replaced with <code>CartesianMonoidalCategory</code>. For this type class, the symbol <code>⊗</code> is the (chosen) binary product, and <code>⨯</code> is reserved for the \"abstract\" categorical product that exists when you have binary products.</p>",
        "id": 519205412,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Carlier",
        "timestamp": 1747683422
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>So in your example, the <code>⨯</code> should be a <code>⊗</code>, and then it should be as you expect</p>",
        "id": 519205543,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Carlier",
        "timestamp": 1747683463
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I see, looks like that was merged just a few days ago? Thanks for the explanation.</p>",
        "id": 519208262,
        "sender_full_name": "Chris Henson",
        "timestamp": 1747684220
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Even before that though, the symbol <code>⊗</code> was for the chosen finite product and <code>⨯</code> for the categorical one, but in any case for applications for cartesian closed stuff you probably want <code>⊗</code> everywhere and forget about <code>⨯</code>.</p>",
        "id": 519209130,
        "sender_full_name": "Robin Carlier",
        "timestamp": 1747684478
    }
]